'''''Social and Personal''''' is one of the longest running columns in ''[[The Irish Times]]''. Previously called '''''Court and Personal''''' it originally published the [[Court Circular]]s of the [[British Royal Family]], the [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland]] and brief [[society reporting]] details of which members of the [[upper class]]  were available in their [[townhouse]]s in [[Dublin]] to receive callers.

=="Court and Personal"==
Following the [[Partition of Ireland]] in 1921, the column covered the [[Governor-General of the Irish Free State]] and [[Governor of Northern Ireland]], with entries placed, as for the Lord Lieutenant, below entries about the Royal Family.  The 1937 [[Constitution of Ireland]] established the office of [[President of Ireland]], whose holder should "take precedence over all other persons in the State".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/cons/en/html#article12_1|title=Constitution of Ireland |work=[[Irish Statute Book]]|page=Article 12.1|nopp=Y|accessdate=17 December 2015}}</ref> The [[Government of the 11th Dáil|Fianna Fáil government]] criticised the column for listing President [[Douglas Hyde]]'s engagements after those of the Royal Family and others, including leading members of the former [[Protestant Ascendancy]] — what [[Frank Aiken]] called "every [[Double-barrelled name#British tradition|hyphenated]] person in the country".<ref>Murphy 2016 pp.147–148; {{cite web|url=http://oireachtasdebates.oireachtas.ie/debates%20authoring/debateswebpack.nsf/takes/dail1944042500023#N178|title=Estimates for Public Services. - Vote No. 63—Army (Resumed).|date=25 April 1944|work=Dáil Éireann Debates|pages=Vol.93 No.10 p.23 cc1536–6 |nopp=Y|accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref> The agreed solution was to place items about the President elsewhere in the paper.<ref>Murphy 2016 pp.148–149</ref> In 1942 the government used its [[Emergency Powers Act 1939|wartime censorship powers]] to remove the column altogether, on the grounds that it compromised [[Irish neutrality during World War II|the state's neutrality]].<ref>Murphy 2016 pp.149–150</ref>

=="Social and Personal"==
Following the  [[Republic of Ireland Act|declaration of the Republic]] in 1949 the column ceased to mention British royalty and gradually abandoned mentioning aristocracy. The name was changed to "Social and Personal".  Until around 1978 it published a daily list of who met the President of Ireland in [[Áras an Uachtaráin]]. The reasons why it stopped doing this remain unclear. The then President, [[Patrick Hillery]] suggested that the paper stopped publishing information being supplied to it. The paper insisted that it stopped receiving information from the Áras.  

Today the column only makes an occasional appearance, to enable a prominent (rarely titled) family to announce forthcoming [[nuptial]]s. Whereas once the column received extensive space daily, gets one or two inches of space on the "[[Letter to the editor|Letters to the Editor]]" page if space allows, and contains often only contains one entry and frequently goes for weeks without being published at all.

