{{Infobox sport governing body |name = Yachting Association of Sri Lanka |abbrev = SRI |logo = Yachting Asoociation of Sri Lanka.png |logosize = 225px |sport = [[Sailing]] |category = |image = |caption = |jurisdiction = [[Sri Lanka]] |founded = {{Start date|1958}} |aff = [[International Sailing Federation|ISAF]] |affdate = 1967 |region = [[Asian Sailing Federation|ASCON]] |regionyear = |headquarters = Level 4, 1 Lake Crescent |location = [[Colombo]] |president = Joseph Kenny |chairman = |chairperson = |chair = |chiefexec = |vicepresident = Senaka Senaviratne |director = |secretary = Chandima Gunawardene |coach = |womenscoach = |key staff = |operating income = |sponsor = |year closed = |replaced = |prevfounded = |url = http://www.yasl.info/ |countryflag = Sri Lanka }}
'''Yachting Association of Sri Lanka''' (YASL) is recognised by the '''[[International Sailing Federation]]'''<ref>http://www.sailing.org/about-isaf/mna/austalia.php ISAF MNA Microsite</ref> as the governing body for the sport of sailing in [[Sri Lanka]].
==Clubs== * Royal Colombo Yacht Club * Ceylon Motor Yacht Club * Dehaweela Sailing Club (closed 1973) * Sri Lanka Navy Sailing Club * Bentota Windsurfing Club * Ruhunu Sailing Association (established 2006) * Kalpitiya Windsports Club
The Royal Colombo Yacht Club (RCYC) was formerly known as 'Colombo Sailing Club'.<ref>[http://www.worldinformation.com/worldroot/start.asp?content=world&continent=Asia&country=094&bodytext=outdoor Basic information]</ref> In 1898 the club received a [[royal charter]] and was renamed to the Royal Colombo Yacht Club. In the 1980s the club had to leave its club house at [[Colombo Harbour]] to accommodate the expansion of the port and for security reasons. The club then shared facilities with the Ceylon Motor Yacht Club at Bolgoda Lake, [[Moratuwa]]. In 2005 a new clubhouse was constructed on the beach at Mt. Lavinia, adjacent to the Lifesaving Association's building.
The Ceylon Motor Yacht Club (CMYC) was established in 1929 and has operated from its current location on the shores of Lake Bolgoda since 1936.
==Events== * Sailing Nationals * South Asian Yachting Regatta (formerly Tri-nation Regatta) * Colombo to Galle Regatta * Royal Thomian Optimist Sailing Regatta * 2006 [[Enterprise (dinghy)|Enterprise]] World Championship * 2011 [[GP14 (dinghy)|GP14]] World Championship * 2012 IODA [[Optimist dinghy|Optimist]] Asian Championship
The YASL has seen its activity much reduced during the past three decades owing to the civil war in the island. Even so, the YASL manages to organize [[regatta]]s regularly, like the '''Janashanthi Sailing Nationals'''.<ref>[http://sundaytimes.lk/071007/Sports/sp213.html Janashanthi Sailing Nationals]</ref> In July 2004 the Yachting Association of Sri Lanka revived the '''Tri-nation Regatta''', in which yachts from [[India]] and [[Pakistan]] compete with local yachts.<ref>[http://pakistantimes.net/2004/07/07/sports2.htm Tri-nation Regatta]</ref> The Sailing Nationals are generally held in January and contested by four different dinghy classes: [[Enterprise (dinghy)|Enterprise]]; [[GP14 (dinghy)|GP14]]; [[Optimist dinghy|Optimist]] and [[Laser (dinghy)|Laser]], together with windsurfers.
The YASL has a sailing school and a small [[Optimist dinghy|Optimist]] fleet.<ref>[http://www.optiworld.org/ioda-develop.html Optimist]</ref>
==Notable competitive sailors== * [[Ray Wijewardene]] - Silver medalist [[Sailing at the 1970 Asian Games|1970 Asian Games]] * [[Lalin Jirasinha]] - Bronze medalist [[Sailing at the 1998 Asian Games|1998 Asian Games]] * [[Krishan Janaka]] - Bronze medalist [[Sailing at the 1998 Asian Games|1998 Asian Games]]
